{{British Royal Family}}

'''Prince William, Duke of Cambridge''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|sep=,|KG|KT|PC|ADC(P)}} (William Arthur Philip Louis;{{#tag:ref|As a member of the Royal Family entitled to be called ''His Royal Highness'', William does not normally use a surname. He has used both ''[[Mountbatten-Windsor]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Lichfield |first=John |date=19 September 2012 |title=William and Kate win legal battle – but lose war to keep topless photos under wraps |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/william-and-kate-win-legal-battle--but-lose-war-to-keep-topless-photos-under-wraps-8153383.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> and – at university and in his military career – ''Wales''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/duke-of-cambridge-to-deploy-to-falklands |title=Duke of Cambridge to deploy to Falklands |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |date=10 November 2011 |accessdate=11 November 2011}}</ref> According to [[letters patent]] of February 1960, his house and family name is ''Windsor''. The middle name Louis is pronounced {{IPAc-en|ˈ|l|uː|i}}.|group = fn|name = sur}} born 21 June 1982) is a member of the [[British royal family]]. He is the elder son of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], and since birth has been second in the [[line of succession to the British throne]] after his father.

William was educated at four schools in the United Kingdom and studied for a degree at the [[University of St. Andrews]]. During a [[gap year]], he spent time in Chile, Belize, and Africa. In December 2006, he completed 44 weeks of training as an officer cadet and was commissioned in the [[Blues and Royals]] regiment. In April 2008, William completed pilot training at [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell]], then underwent helicopter flight training and became a full-time pilot with the [[RAF Search and Rescue Force]] in early 2009. His service with the British Armed Forces ended in September 2013.<ref name="Withnall">{{cite news |last=Withnall |first=Adam |date=12 September 2013 |title=Prince William completes last shift as RAF pilot to take up full-time job of being royal |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/prince-william-completes-last-shift-as-raf-pilot-to-take-up-fulltime-job-of-being-royal-8811642.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="BBC Swap">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24065166 |title=Prince William to swap armed forces for royal and charity duties |publisher=BBC News |date=12 September 2013 |accessdate=12 September 2013}}</ref>

William [[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton|married]] [[Catherine Middleton]] on 29 April 2011 at [[Westminster Abbey]]. Hours before the wedding, he was created [[Duke of Cambridge]], [[Earl of Strathearn]], and [[Baron Carrickfergus]]. The couple have three children; [[Prince George of Cambridge|Prince George]], [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge|Princess Charlotte]], and [[Prince Louis of Cambridge|Prince Louis]].

{{toclimit|4}}

==Early life==
Prince William was born at Lindo Wing of [[St Mary's Hospital, London]], at 9:03{{nbsp}}pm on 21 June 1982 as the first child of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]—[[heir apparent]] to [[Queen Elizabeth II]]—and [[Diana, Princess of Wales]].<ref name=evnews81/><ref name=official>{{cite web|url=http://www.dukeandduchessofcambridge.org/the-duke-of-cambridge/biography|title=The Duke of Cambridge – Biography|publisher=Office of the Prince of Wales|accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=49027 |page=8215 |date=21 June 1982 }}</ref> His names, William Arthur Philip Louis, were announced by Buckingham Palace on 28 June.<ref name="evnews81">{{cite news|title=Prince William's his name|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=K4RGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nDINAAAAIBAJ&pg=1118,3639121&dq=diana+spencer&hl=en|accessdate=23 July 2013|newspaper=The Evening News|date=28 July 1982|agency=AP|location=London}}</ref> He was [[baptism|baptised]] by the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Robert Runcie]], in the Music Room of [[Buckingham Palace]] on 4 August, the 82nd birthday of his paternal great-grandmother [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] .<ref name="pbp5aug">{{cite news|title=William baptized|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9f8sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=es0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=3834,2455732&dq=princess+diana&hl=en|accessdate=31 May 2013|newspaper=The Palm Beach Post|date=5 August 1982|agency=AP|location=London}}</ref>{{refn|group="fn"|William had six godparents: former King [[Constantine II of Greece]] (his paternal second cousin once removed); [[Princess Alexandra, Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Mrs Ogilvy]] (his paternal first cousin twice removed); the [[Natalia Grosvenor, Duchess of Westminster|Duchess of Westminster]]; [[Lady Susan Hussey]]; [[Norton Knatchbull, 8th Baron Brabourne|Lord Romsey]] (his paternal second cousin once removed); and Sir [[Laurens van der Post]].<ref name="evnews81" /><ref name="Yvonne">{{cite web|url=http://users.uniserve.com/~canyon/christenings.htm#Christenings|title=Yvonne's Royalty Home Page – Royal Christenings |publisher=Uniserve|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>}} He was the first child born to a Prince and Princess of Wales since [[Prince John of the United Kingdom|Prince John]] in 1905.<ref>{{cite news|title=Princess Diana enters hospital in early labor|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MyBAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cFgMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2686,2259663&dq=frances+ruth+roche&hl=en|accessdate=21 July 2013|newspaper=Youngstown Vindicator|date=21 June 1982|agency=AP|location=London}}</ref> William's parents affectionately called him "Wombat"<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19190534/ns/dateline_nbc-a_conversation_with_william_and_harry/ Dateline NBC], ''[[NBC]]'', 6 October 2007</ref> or "Wills"—a name coined by the press.<ref name="The Sunday Herald">{{Cite news|title=The Saint that looked after Wills|work=The Sunday Herald|date=26 June 2005|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com}}</ref>

[[File:Queen Elizabeth, Prince Philip, and grandchildren (11440082454) (cropped1).jpg|thumb|left|William (far left) on a 1987 Christmas card with his grandparents, brother, and cousins [[Peter Phillips|Peter]] and [[Zara Phillips]]]]

Since his birth, William has been second in the [[line of succession to the British throne]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.royal.uk/succession|title=Succession|publisher=Royal Household |date=30 May 2016 |accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> At age seven, he reportedly told his mother he wanted to be a police officer when he was older so that he might be able to protect her; a statement to which his five-year-old brother [[Prince Harry|Harry]] reportedly replied, "Oh, no you can't. You've got to be King."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/26/prince-william-profile-royal-wedding|title=Prince William: how he has coped with a life in the spotlight|last=Bates|first=Stephen|date=2011-04-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> 

William began accompanying his parents on official visits at an early age. In 1983, he accompanied them on a tour to Australia and New Zealand,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/theprinceofwales/atwork/supportingthequeen/countriesvisited/index.html |title=The Prince of Wales – Countries Visited |publisher=Princeofwales.gov.uk |accessdate=15 October 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202113324/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/theprinceofwales/atwork/supportingthequeen/countriesvisited/index.html |archivedate=2 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> a decision made by Diana. The decision was considered to be unconventional because the first- and second-in-line to the throne would be travelling together, and because of William's young age.<ref name="people1" /> His first public appearance was on 1 March 1991—[[Saint David's Day]]—during an official visit of his parents to [[Cardiff]]. After arriving by aeroplane, William was taken to [[Llandaff Cathedral]] where he signed the visitors' book, showing he is left-handed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/gloucestershire/content/articles/2005/05/03/prince_william_feature.shtml|title=The young royals: Prince William|publisher=BBC|date=3 May 2005|accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref>

On 3 June 1991, William was admitted to [[Royal Berkshire Hospital]] after being accidentally hit on the forehead by a fellow student wielding a golf club. He suffered a depressed fracture of the skull and was operated on at [[Great Ormond Street Hospital]], resulting in a permanent scar.<ref name="university">{{cite web|url =http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/prince_william_marks_the_end_of_the_first_term_of_his_third__1470010393.html|title =Prince William marks the end of the first term of his third university year with an interview|accessdate =31 May 2008|date =14 December 2003|publisher =Prince of Wales|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20081025092622/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/prince_william_marks_the_end_of_the_first_term_of_his_third__1470010393.html|archive-date =25 October 2008|dead-url =yes|df =dmy-all}}</ref> In a 2009 interview, he dubbed this scar a "[[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] scar" and said, "I call it that because it glows sometimes and some people notice it—other times they don't notice it at all".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/5011509/Prince-William-has-Harry-Potter-scar-from-golf-accident.html|title=Prince William has 'Harry Potter' scar from golf accident|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=UK|date=18 March 2009 |first=Andrew|last=Pierce}}</ref>

William's mother wanted him and his younger brother [[Prince Harry|Harry]] to have wider experiences than are usual for royal children. She took them to [[Walt Disney World]] and [[McDonald's]], as well as [[AIDS]] clinics and shelters for the homeless, and bought them items typically owned by teenagers, such as video games.<ref name="people1">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/prince_william/biography|title=Prince William Biography|newspaper=People|accessdate=15 October 2008}}</ref> Diana, who was by then divorced from Charles, [[Death of Diana, Princess of Wales|died in a car accident]] in the early hours of 31 August 1997. William, then aged 15, together with  his 12-year-old brother and their father, were staying at [[Balmoral Castle]] at the time. The Prince of Wales waited until his sons awoke the following morning to tell them about their mother's death.<ref>{{Cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/conspiracy_files/6217366.stm |title=Timeline: How Diana died |publisher=BBC News |date=14 December 2006 |accessdate=15 October 2008}}</ref> William accompanied his father, brother, paternal grandfather [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], and his maternal uncle [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer]], at his [[Funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales|mother's funeral]]; they walked behind the funeral cortège from Buckingham Palace to [[Westminster Abbey]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/6/newsid_2502000/2502307.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY – 6–1997: Diana's funeral watched by millions|publisher=BBC|date=6 September 1997|location=London|accessdate=26 March 2009}}</ref>

==Education==

William was educated at [[independent school (United Kingdom)|independent schools]], starting at Jane Mynors' nursery school and the pre-preparatory [[Wetherby School]], both in London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wetherby Pre-Preparatory School|url=http://www.londonpreprep.com/schools/boys/wetherby-school/|publisher=London Pre-Prep|accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> Following this, he attended [[Ludgrove School]] near [[Wokingham]], Berkshire, and was privately tutored during summers by [[Rory Stewart]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/26/rory-stewart-penrith-tory-seat |location=London |work= [[The Guardian]] | first=Allegra | last=Stratton | title=Former royal tutor Rory Stewart selected for safe Tory seat | date=26 October 2009}}</ref> At Ludgrove, he participated in [[association football|football]], swimming, basketball, [[clay pigeon shooting]], and [[cross country running]]. He sat the entrance exam to [[Eton College]] and was admitted. There, he studied Geography, Biology, and History of Art at [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]], obtaining an 'A' in Geography, a 'C' in Biology, and a 'B' in History of Art.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/prince_william_gives_an_interview_at_the_start_of_his_univer_422216032.html |title=Prince William gives an interview at the start of his university career |date=22 September 2001 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113130840/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/prince_william_gives_an_interview_at_the_start_of_his_univer_422216032.html |archivedate=13 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=What is it like at Eton College? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4634031.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=4 July 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bates |first=Stephen |date=18 August 2000 |title=William makes the grade |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/aug/18/alevels2000.alevels4 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> At Eton, he took up [[water polo]] and continued to play football, captaining his house team.<ref name="princeofwales1">{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/princewilliam/interests/ |title=The Prince of Wales – Interests |publisher=Princeofwales.gov.uk |accessdate=15 October 2008 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080616074353/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/princewilliam/interests/ |archivedate =16 June 2008}}</ref>

The decision to place William in Eton went against the family tradition of sending royal children to [[Gordonstoun]], which William's grandfather, father, two uncles, and two cousins all attended. Diana's father and brother both attended Eton.<ref name="people1" /> The Royal Family and the tabloid press agreed William would be allowed to study free from intrusion in exchange for regular updates about his life. The chairman of the [[Press Complaints Commission]] [[John Wakeham]] said of the arrangement, "Prince William is not an institution; nor a soap star; nor a football hero. He is a boy: in the next few years, perhaps the most important and sometimes painful part of his life, he will grow up and become a man."<ref name="people1" />

After completing his studies at Eton, William took a gap year, during which he took part in [[British Army]] training exercises in Belize,<ref name="BBC Belize">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Rugged prince scores PR triumph |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1064991.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=11 December 2000 |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> worked on English dairy farms, visited Africa,<ref>Prince of Wales.gov [http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/thedukeandduchessofcambridge/thedukeofcambridge/biography/gapyear/ personalprofiles] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110602083612/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/thedukeandduchessofcambridge/thedukeofcambridge/biography/gapyear/ |date=2 June 2011 }} & royal.gov [https://www.royal.uk/the-duke-of-cambridge The Duke of Cambridge] Retrieved 8 February 2012</ref> and for ten weeks taught children in southern Chile. As part of the [[Raleigh International]] program in the town of [[Tortel]], William lived with other young volunteers, sharing in the common household chores—including cleaning the toilet—and also volunteered as a guest disc jockey at a local radio station.<ref name="BBC Belize" /> His interest in African culture prompted him to teach himself [[Swahili language|Swahili]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2003/06/21/prince-william-celebrates-21st-birthday-with-african-themed-party.html|title=Prince William Celebrates 21st Birthday With African-Themed Party|publisher=Fox News|date=21 June 2003|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref>

By 2001, William was back in the United Kingdom and had enrolled at the [[University of St Andrews]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Summerskill |first=Ben |author-link=Ben Summerskill |date=23 September 2001 |title=Welcome to Will's new world |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/sep/23/education.students |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |location=London |accessdate=15 October 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Howie |first=Michael |date=24 June 2005 |title= William Wales M.A. collects his degree |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/william-wales-m-a-collects-his-degree-1-717426 |newspaper=[[The Scotsman]] |accessdate=15 October 2008}}</ref> News of this caused a temporary increase in the number of applications to St Andrews, mostly from young women who wanted an opportunity to meet him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/prince_william_gives_an_interview_at_the_start_of_his_univer_422216032.html |title=The Prince of Wales – Prince William gives an interview at the start of his university career |publisher=Princeofwales.gov.uk |date=22 September 2001 |accessdate=15 October 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113130840/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/news/prince_william_gives_an_interview_at_the_start_of_his_univer_422216032.html |archivedate=13 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The extra attention did not deter him; he embarked on a degree course in [[History of art|Art History]], later changing his main subject to Geography, and earned a [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|Scottish Master of Arts degree]] with [[British undergraduate degree classification|upper second class honours]]. While at university, he represented the Scottish national universities water polo team at the Celtic Nations tournament in 2004.<ref name="princeofwales1" /> He was known as "Steve" by other students to avoid any journalists overhearing and realising his identity.<ref name="The Sunday Herald" />

William returned to St Andrews in February 2011 as patron of the university's 600th Anniversary Appeal.<ref>St-Andrews University (charity registered No SC013532) [http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/news/archive/2011/Title,65130,en.html News/archive] – Andreea Nemes [http://www.thesaint-online.com/2011/03/royal-visit-launches-600th-anniversary/ thesaint-online] Retrieved 27 January 2012</ref>

To prepare for his eventual management of the [[Duchy of Cornwall]], in 2014 William enrolled in a vocational agricultural management course at Cambridge, which was organised by the [[Cambridge Programme for Sustainability Leadership]] (CPSL), of which his father is patron.<ref name="arbiter">{{cite news|title=Opinion: Why Prince William is right to go back to school|author=Victoria Arbiter |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/08/opinion/prince-william-school/|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=[[CNN]]|date=8 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-25639442|title=Prince William begins agriculture course at Cambridge|publisher=BBC|date=7 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-william/10542703/Duke-of-Cambridge-to-study-agriculture-at-Cambridge-University.html|title=Duke of Cambridge to study agriculture at Cambridge University|publisher=Telegraph Media|author=Rayner, Gordon|date=30 December 2013}}</ref> The estate is a "£760 million (about $1.25 billion) entity established in 1337 to provide a private income for use by the reigning monarch's eldest son", which William will inherit if his father becomes king.<ref name="arbiter"/>

==Military and air ambulance service==

===Military training and secondments===
Having decided to follow a military career, in October 2005 William attended the four-day [[Army Officer Selection Board|Regular Commissions Board]] at [[Westbury, Wiltshire|Westbury]] in Wiltshire, where he underwent selection to judge his suitability to become an army officer. He passed selection and was admitted to the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] in January 2006.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1501217/Prince-William-to-join-his-brother-at-Sandhurst.html |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London | title=Prince William to join his brother at Sandhurst | first=Caroline | last=Davies | date=22 October 2005 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> After completing the course, William was commissioned as a Second Lieutenant at Sandhurst on 15 December 2006; the graduation parade was attended by the Queen and the Prince of Wales, along with other members of the Royal Family. William officially received his commission as a [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] at midnight. As "Lieutenant Wales"—a name based on his father's title Prince of Wales—he followed his younger brother<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5367862.stm |title=William joining Harry's regiment |publisher=BBC News |date=21 September 2006 |accessdate=17 November 2010}}</ref> into the [[Blues and Royals]] as a troop commander in an armoured reconnaissance unit, after which he spent four months training for the post at [[Bovington Camp]], Dorset.

Though [[Major-General (United Kingdom)|Major-General]] [[Sir Sebastian Roberts]], General Officer commanding the [[Household Division]], had said William's deployment was possible, the Prince's position as second-in-line to the throne and the convention of ministers advising against placing that person into dangerous situations cast doubts on William's chances of seeing combat. These doubts increased after Prince Harry's deployment was cancelled in 2007 due to "specific threats". William, instead, went on to train in the [[Royal Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force]], obtaining his commission as a [[sub-lieutenant]] in the former and [[flying officer]] in the latter—both broadly equivalent to the army rank of lieutenant. After completing his training, William undertook an attachment with the Royal Air Force, undergoing an intensive, four-month training course at [[RAF Cranwell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meeja.com.au/index.php?display_article_id=217 |title=Prince William ready for Search and Rescue role |publisher=meeja.com.au |date=16 September 2008 |accessdate=16 September 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019214531/http://www.meeja.com.au/index.php?display_article_id=217 |archivedate=19 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="Pierce">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/theroyalfamily/4218703/Prince-William-starts-as-a-search-and-rescue-helicopter-pilot.html |title=Prince William starts as a search and rescue helicopter pilot |accessdate=18 January 2009 |last=Pierce |first=Andrew |date=13 January 2009 |work= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London }}</ref> Upon completing the course on 11 April 2008, he was presented with his [[Aircrew brevet|RAF wings]] by his father,<ref name="smh1">{{Cite news|author = Staff | url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/kate-watches-william-get-his-wings/2008/04/12/1207856847954.html |title=Kate watches William get his wings | publisher = [[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]] (via ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'') |date=12 April 2008|accessdate= 26 July 2013}}</ref> who had received his own wings after training at Cranwell.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7340692.stm |title=Prince William awarded RAF wings |publisher=BBC News |date=11 April 2008 |accessdate=2 July 2008}}</ref> During this secondment, William flew to Afghanistan in a [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17 Globemaster]] that repatriated the body of Trooper Robert Pearson.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7374589.stm |title=William visits Afghanistan troops |publisher=BBC News |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=30 August 2008}}</ref>

William was then seconded to train with the Royal Navy from June to August 2008, during which he spent three weeks at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] training on units of the surface fleet and submarines, as well as with the [[Fleet Air Arm]] and the [[Royal Marines]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7429261.stm |title=William's Navy posting revealed |publisher=BBC News |date=31 May 2008 |accessdate=31 May 2008}}</ref> He spent a day on submarine [[HMS Talent (S92)|HMS ''Talent'']].<ref>{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Nick |date=20 June 2008 |title=Prince William in secret submarine mission |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/2162027/Prince-William-in-secret-submarine-mission.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=30 August 2008}}</ref> During a five-week deployment on [[HMS Iron Duke (F234)|HMS ''Iron Duke'']] in the Caribbean, he took part in a joint operation with the [[United States Coast Guard]] that identified and captured a speedboat carrying {{Convert|900|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of [[cocaine]] worth about £40&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/europe/07/02/prince.william/index.html |title=Prince William helps bust $80m drug smuggling boat |work=CNN |date=2 July 2008 |accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7485365.stm |title=William's ship seizes drugs haul |publisher=BBC News |date=3 July 2008 |accessdate=30 August 2008}}</ref> The ship also took part in other raids.<ref>{{cite news |last=Browning |first=Eliza |date=28 July 2008 |title=Prince William in Caribbean Drug Bust |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/story?id=5461747 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=30 August 2008}}</ref>

Because of William's future royal role, a long-term career in the military was considered out-of-the-question; due to his position, his desire to see active service was unlikely to be fulfilled. William originally joined the military on a short-service commission lasting three years. It was announced in September 2008, however, that he would be extending his forces career in 2008 by accepting another secondment that included working at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MOD) and non-operational flying with the Army Air Corps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/prince_william_military_secondments_in_autumn_2008_1233465855.html|title=Prince William: Military Secondments in Autumn, 2008|date=31 July 2008|publisher=princeofwales.gov.uk|accessdate=30 August 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915053013/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/prince_william_military_secondments_in_autumn_2008_1233465855.html|archivedate=15 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was later announced that he would transfer from the Army to the RAF to train as a full-time [[search and rescue]] helicopter pilot, a role that would enable him to take an active role in the armed forces without being deployed on combat operations.

===Royal Air Force service===
[[File:HRH Prince William Pilots Seaking Helicopter During Search and Rescue Exercise MOD 45151868.jpg|thumb|[[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] helicopter being flown by William in 2010]]

In January 2009, William transferred his commission to the RAF and was promoted to [[Flight Lieutenant]]. He trained to become a helicopter pilot with the RAF's [[RAF Search and Rescue Force|Search and Rescue Force]]. In January 2010, he graduated from the [[Defence Helicopter Flying School]] at [[RAF Shawbury]], where he had been under the instruction of Squadron Leader Craig Finch.<ref name="bonnett">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Prince-William-Graduates-From-Advanced-Helicopter-Training-Prince-Charles-Presents-Certificate/Article/201001315524625?lpos=UK_News_Top_Stories_Header_4&lid=ARTICLE_15524625_Prince_William_Graduates_From_Advanced_Helicopter_Training%2C_Prince_Charles_Presents_Certificate|title=Royal Heir Force: Prince's Career Takes Off|last=Bonnett|first=Tom|date=15 January 2010|work=[[Sky News]]|accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref> On 26 January 2010, he transferred to the Search and Rescue Training Unit at [[RAF Valley]], [[Anglesey]], to receive training on the [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] search and rescue helicopter; he graduated from this course on 17 September 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8480634.stm |title=Prince William starts RAF rescue training on Anglesey |publisher=BBC News |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref> This made him the first member of the British royal family since [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] to live in Wales.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Tatler List – Duke of Cambridge |url=http://www.tatler.com/the-tatler-list/p/duke-of-cambridge |publisher=[[Tatler]] |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>

It was announced on 15 April 2010 that William would remain at RAF Valley for his operational tour; he was assigned to C Flight [[No. 22 Squadron RAF|No. 22 Squadron]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Richard |date=12 September 2013 |title=Preparing to be King: Prince William says goodbye to RAF after more than seven years |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/428836/Preparing-to-be-King-Prince-William-says-goodbye-to-RAF-after-more-than-seven-years |newspaper=[[Daily Express|Sunday Express]] |location=London |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> and initially performed co-pilot duties.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bingham |first=John |date=15 April 2010 |title=Prince William to be posted to RAF base on Anglesey |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/7593810/Prince-William-to-be-posted-to-RAF-base-on-Anglesey.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> His operational tour was expected to last 30 to 36 months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive.cfm?storyid=65D7729A-1143-EC82-2E3FE8BEE1F37F89 |title=Prince William set to join RAF Search and Rescue |date=15 September 2008 |publisher=[[Royal Air Force]] |accessdate=15 September 2008}}</ref>

[[File:Prince William of Wales RAF.jpg|thumb|left|William wearing the uniform of a Flight Lieutenant]]
William's first rescue mission as co-pilot of an RAF Sea King was a response to an emergency call from the Liverpool Coastguard on 2 October 2010. William—who was excited to take part in an active mission—and the other three crew members, flew from their base at RAF Valley to an offshore gas rig in [[Morecambe Bay]], from where a man who had suffered a suspected heart attack was airlifted to hospital.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-11476357 |title=Co-pilot Prince William rescues man from oil rig |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=5 October 2010 |accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> In November 2011, he participated in a search-and-rescue mission involving a cargo ship that was sinking in the Irish Sea; William, as a co-pilot, helped rescue two sailors.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bingham |first1=John |last2=Bunyan |first2=Nigel |date=27 November 2011 |title=Prince William spearheads rescue for stricken Russian sailors |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-william/8918754/Prince-William-spearheads-rescue-for-stricken-Russian-sailors.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref>

William was deployed to the [[Falkland Islands]] for a six-week tour with [[No. 1564 Flight RAF|No. 1564 Flight]] from February to March 2012.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/prince-william-to-deploy-to-falkland-islands-1.724090 |publisher=[[CTV News]] |title=Prince William to deploy to Falkland Islands |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=11 November 2011  |accessdate=11 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/feb/02/prince-william-falklands-falkland-islands |title=Prince William arrives in the Falkland Islands |newspaper=The Guardian |agency=[[Press Association]] |date=3 February 2012 |accessdate=11 February 2012}}</ref> The Argentine government condemned the Duke's deployment to the islands close to the 30th anniversary of the beginning of the [[Falklands War]] as a "provocative act".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-15703340|title=Argentina condemns Prince William Falklands posting |publisher=BBC News |date=11 November 2011 |accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goñi |first=Uki |author-link=Uki Goñi |date=1 February 2012 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/feb/01/argentina-prince-william-falklands |title=Argentina criticises Prince William's tour of duty of Falkland Islands |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=11 February 2012}}</ref>

In June 2012 Prince William gained a qualification to be captain or [[pilot in command]] of a Sea King rather than a co-pilot.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Prince William to command search and rescue missions |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18354699 |publisher=BBC News |date=7 June 2012 |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> His active service as an RAF search-and-rescue pilot ended in September 2013.<ref name="Withnall" /><ref name="BBC Swap"/>

===Air ambulance pilot===

In 2014, it was announced that William would accept a full-time role as a pilot with the [[East Anglian Air Ambulance]] (EAAA) based at [[Cambridge Airport]]. Despite his qualifications as a military helicopter pilot, William needed a civil pilot's licence and further training before being permitted to take command of the Air Ambulance. Although his position is paid, it was announced that William would donate his full salary, estimated at about £40,000 per year, to the EAAA charity.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-28685666 |title=Prince William to join East Anglian Air Ambulance |publisher=BBC News |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> He underwent part of his training as an EAAA pilot at [[Norwich International Airport|Norwich Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/prince_william_starts_training_for_east_anglian_air_ambulance_job_at_norwich_airport_1_4015527 |title=Prince William starts training for East Anglian Air Ambulance job at Norwich airport|author=Rosa McMahon |work=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref> On 13 July 2015, William started his new job, which he felt was a natural progression from his previous role as an RAF search-and-rescue pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/video/2015/jul/13/prince-william-air-ambulance-pilot-video|title=Prince William starts new job as air ambulance pilot|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He left his position with EAAA in July 2017 to assume a more active role in royal duties on behalf of his grandmother the Queen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-40728530 |title=Prince William pilots last East Anglian Air Ambulance shift |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=27 July 2017 |website=BBC News |publisher= |access-date=2 March 2018 |quote=}}</ref>

==Royal duties==
{{see also|List of official overseas trips made by Prince William, Duke of Cambridge}}

Upon graduation from university, William began to undertake public duties of his own, as well as obtaining private work experience by interning in [[land management]] at [[Chatsworth House]] and in banking at [[HSBC]].<ref name="people1" />

At the age of 21, Prince William was appointed as a [[Counsellor of State]], and first served in that capacity when the Queen was in Nigeria to attend the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2003|Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] in 2003. For his 21st birthday, William accompanied his father on a tour of Wales, visiting the Anglesey Food Fair and opening a centre for the homeless in Newport.<ref name="POWBioGrow">{{cite web| url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/princewilliam/biography/growingup/index.html |title=The Prince of Wales: Prince William: Biography: Growing Up |publisher=Clarence House |accessdate=16 October 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615161213/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/princewilliam/biography/growingup/index.html| archivedate=15 June 2008}}</ref> By July 2005, he was on his first solo overseas tour, travelling to New Zealand, to participate in World War II commemorations on behalf of his grandmother in her role as [[Monarchy of New Zealand|Queen of New Zealand]]. For the 30th anniversary of his father's charity, [[The Prince's Trust]], William and his brother were interviewed together for the first time by television personalities [[Ant & Dec]].<ref name="POWBioGrow" />

[[Tina Brown]] said in her 2007 biography of Diana, Princess of Wales, that Prince William had, like his father, expressed a desire to become [[Governor-General of Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/29/asia/AS-GEN-Australia-Britain-Prince-William.php |title=Australian leaders dismiss the idea of Prince William as governor-general |work=International Herald Tribune |accessdate=15 October 2008}}</ref> [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[John Howard]] said: "We have for a long time embraced the idea that the person who occupies that post should be in every way an Australian citizen."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/william-for-gg-not-on-pm/2007/06/29/1182624122159.html|title=William for GG not on: PM|date=29 June 2007|accessdate=30 August 2008 | work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>

In 2009, a private office was set up for William by his grandmother, with Sir [[David Manning]] as his adviser.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/8305721/Mentor-helps-Kate-Middleton-prepare-for-Royal-life.html |title=Mentor helps Kate Middleton prepare for Royal life |last=Nikkhah |first=Roya |date=10 February 2011 |work=Telegraph.co.uk |access-date=23 July 2013}}</ref>

Manning personally accompanied him in January 2010 as he toured [[Auckland]] and [[Wellington]] on behalf of the Queen; William opened the new building of the [[Supreme Court of New Zealand]] and was welcomed by a [[Māori people|Māori]] [[Tribal chief|chief]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10620877 |title=Prince William's royal magic captures the crowds |date=18 January 2010 |work=The New Zealand Herald |access-date=19 January 2010 |agency=New Zealand Press Association}}</ref> William succeeded [[Richard Attenborough|Lord Attenborough]] in 2010 as the fifth president of the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/news,1029,BA.html |title=Prince William Appointed Academy President |publisher=[[BAFTA]] |date=21 February 2010 |accessdate=5 March 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903055554/http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/news,1029,BA.html |archivedate=3 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In March 2011, William visited [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, after the recent [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|earthquake]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/mar/17/prince-william-christchurch-earthquake-damage |title=Prince William tours Christchurch earthquake damage |last=Manhire |first=Toby |date=17 March 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=23 July 2013 |location=London}}</ref> and spoke at the memorial service at [[Hagley Park, Christchurch|Hagley Park]], on behalf of his grandmother.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10713379 |title=Service inspires weary Cantabrians |last=Booker |first=Jarrod |date=18 March 2011 |work=The New Zealand Herald |access-date=29 April 2011}}</ref> Upon leaving New Zealand, William travelled to Australia, to visit areas badly affected by flooding in the states of [[Queensland]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref>{{cite web|author= Mclean, Tamara |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/world/australia/4787916/Prince-William-heads-to-Queensland |title=Prince William heads to Queensland |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=19 March 2011 |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/christchurch-quake-memorial-service-happened-4071417/video?vid=4071991 | publisher=TVNZ One News | title=Christchurch quake memorial service: As it happened | date=18 March 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> After twice accompanying his parents to Canada, Prince William, with his wife, [[2011 royal tour of Canada|toured the country]] and visited the United States in June and July 2011, attending [[Canada Day]] celebrations on [[Parliament Hill]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/939727--royal-newlyweds-are-coming-to-canada-but-not-toronto?bn=1 |title=Royal newlyweds are coming to Canada, but not Toronto |last=Campion-Smith |first=Bruce |date=16 February 2011 |work=Toronto Star |access-date=16 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title=Queen calls Canada 'example to the world'| publisher=CBC| date=1 July 2010| url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/07/01/canada-day001.html| accessdate=16 February 2011}}</ref> On 2 November, the Duke and Duchess visited the [[UNICEF]] Supply Division Centre for supplying food to malnourished African children in [[Copenhagen|Copenhagen, Denmark]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-15556875 | publisher=BBC News | title=William and Kate visit Unicef famine relief depot in Copenhagen | date=2 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org.uk/Latest/Photo-stories/william-kate-east-africa-photos/ |title=Photo story: William and Kate visit UNICEF Supply Centre |publisher=unicef.org.uk |date=2 November 2011 |accessdate=25 December 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106141956/http://www.unicef.org.uk/Latest/Photo-stories/william-kate-east-africa-photos/ |archivedate=6 January 2012 |df= }}</ref> In September 2012, they toured [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Tuvalu]] and the [[Solomon Islands]] as part of the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Diamond Jubilee celebrations]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Singh|first1=Anita|title=Jubilee: royal trip to paradise for Duke and Duchess|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/8957142/Jubilee-royal-trip-to-paradise-for-Duke-and-Duchess.html|accessdate=28 October 2015|work=The Telegraph|date=15 December 2011}}</ref>

In April 2014, the Duke and Duchess undertook a royal tour together to New Zealand and Australia. From 20–21 September, he took his wife's place on a tour of [[Malta]], for the island's 50th anniversary of its independence from Britain.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-29283973 |title=Prince William visits Malta in place of pregnant Kate |date=20 September 2014 |work=BBC News }}</ref> On 21 October, the Duke and Duchess met the [[President of Singapore]] [[Tony Tan]] as part of his state visit to the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore State Visit programme |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/StateVisitprogrammes/2014/SingaporeStateVisitprogramme.aspx |accessdate=22 October 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022042540/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/StateVisitprogrammes/2014/SingaporeStateVisitprogramme.aspx |archivedate=22 October 2014 }}</ref> In December 2014, he met U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in the [[Oval Office]], publicly advocating against illegal wildlife trade.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-30382449 |title=Prince William holds first talks with President Obama |work=BBC News}}</ref>

In 2015, Prince William visited [[Beijing]], [[Shanghai]] and [[Yunnan]] in China from 1 to 4 March. Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]] welcomed him as he began the first visit to the mainland by a member of the British royal family in almost three decades.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-william/11443884/Prince-William-arrives-in-China-and-invites-President-Xi-for-state-visit.html |title=Prince William arrives in China and invites President Xi for state visit |date=2 March 2015 |access-date=25 December 2015 |publisher=The Telegraph |agency=Reuters}}</ref>

[[File:Prince William, Duke of Cambridge and Tel Aviv mayor Ron Huldai.jpg|thumb|William and the mayor of Tel Aviv, [[Ron Huldai]], in Israel, June 2018]]
In June 2018, Prince William visited [[Israel]] and [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], being the first British royal to visit the area officially since the expiry of the [[British Mandate for Palestine (legal instrument)|British Mandate]]. He visited [[Tel Aviv]], meeting with mayor [[Ron Huldai]] and touring the beach area and city centre; Jerusalem, meeting with President [[Reuven Rivlin]] and Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]; and [[Ramallah]], meeting with Palestinian president [[Mahmoud Abbas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5297273,00.html |title=The British interest behind Prince William's Israel visit |last=Nadav |first=Eyal |date=26 June 2018 |website=ynetnews.co.il |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

==Personal interests==

Following his parents' examples, William took interest in various causes from a relatively early age. His mother's charitable work with HIV/AIDS aid and prevention and his father's work with the natural environment and the inner-city disadvantaged directed William into those areas. He also showed a desire to focus on the needy in Africa, sometimes working with his brother's charity, [[Sentebale]].

===Humanitarian and environmental causes===
William became aware of HIV/AIDS in the mid-1990s, when his mother began to take her two sons to visit shelters and clinics for those suffering from the disease. In January 2005, William and his brother volunteered at a British [[Red Cross]] aid distribution centre to pack emergency supplies for countries that were affected by the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Boxing Day tsunami]].<ref name="WillsPatron">{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5999.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204011941/http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5999.asp |archivedate=4 February 2009 |title=The Royal Family – HRH The Prince of Wales – Prince William – Charities and Patronages |publisher=Buckingham Palace |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref> Later, in September, William granted his [[patronage]] to [[Centrepoint (charity)|Centrepoint]], a charity that assists the homeless.<ref name="POWPatron">{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/princewilliamprinceharry/princewilliam/atwork/charitiesandpatronages/ |title=The Prince of Wales – Prince William – At Work – Charities and Patronages |publisher=Clarence House |accessdate=29 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429161757/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/personalprofiles/princewilliamprinceharry/princewilliam/atwork/charitiesandpatronages/ |archivedate=29 April 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref name="centrepoint">{{cite web|title=Centrepoint – Our patron |url=http://www.centrepoint.org.uk/our-patron |accessdate=29 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501110502/http://www.centrepoint.org.uk/our-patron |archivedate=1 May 2011 |df= }}</ref> During the period when his mother had been patron of Centrepoint, he had accompanied her on visits to its headquarters and projects.

William also worked in the children's unit at [[The Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust|The Royal Marsden Hospital]] for two days of work experience in 2005, as well as helping out in the medical research, catering, and fund raising departments.<ref name="POWPatron" /> The same year, he spent two weeks in North Wales with a [[Mountain rescue in England and Wales|mountain rescue team]].<ref name="WillsPatron" /> In May 2007, William became patron of both organisations (his mother had also previously been patron of the Royal Marsden Hospital) and he became attracted to Mountain Rescue England and Wales in order to, in his words, "highlight and celebrate the vital, selfless and courageous work of our mountain rescue organisations".<ref name="POWPatron" />

Prince William also became a patron of the [[Tusk Trust]] in December 2005,<ref name="POWPatron" /> a charity that works towards conserving wildlife and initiating community development, including providing education, across Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tusk.org/about-us/ |title=About Us |publisher=Tusk Trust |accessdate=7 August 2018 }}</ref> He became associated with the organisation after he witnessed its work first hand in Africa. Saying "rural African initiatives that foster education, responsibility and participation in the local community light the way to conservation",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cycleoflife2008.com/content/pwquote.asp |title=Cycle of Life: News |publisher=Cycle of Life |year=2007 |accessdate=29 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708214938/http://www.cycleoflife2008.com/content/pwquote.asp |archivedate=8 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> he carried out his first official duty with the trust in launching a {{convert|5000|mi|km|adj=on}} bike ride across the African continent in 2007. In 2010, he also became a patron of [[100 Women in Hedge Funds]] Philanthropic Initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/prince_william_to_become_patron_of_100_women_in_hedge_funds__1457625743.html|title=Prince William to become Patron of 100 Women in Hedge Funds' philanthropic initiatives|accessdate=13 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113130749/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/prince_william_to_become_patron_of_100_women_in_hedge_funds__1457625743.html|archive-date=13 January 2012|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In March 2011, the Duke and Duchess set up a gift fund held by [[The Royal Foundation of The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge and Prince Harry|The Foundation of Prince William and Prince Harry]] to allow well-wishers who wanted to give them a wedding gift to donate money to charities instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalweddingcharityfund.org/ |title=The Prince William & Miss Catherine Middleton Charitable Gift Fund |publisher=royalweddingcharityfund.org |accessdate=4 February 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318110546/http://www.royalweddingcharityfund.org/ |archivedate=18 March 2011 |df= }}</ref> The gift fund supported 26 charities of the couple's choice, incorporating the armed forces, children, the elderly, art, sport and conservation. These causes are close to their hearts and reflect the experiences, passions and values of their lives so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8385866/William-and-Kate-ask-for-charity-donations-in-lieu-of-wedding-gifts.html |title=William and Kate ask for charity donations in lieu of wedding gifts –  Prince William and Kate Middleton have asked wedding guests and well wishers to donate to their own special charitable fund rather than give them presents, St James's Palace has announced | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate= 23 July 2013 |first=Victoria |last=Ward}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = Holden, Michael | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/16/us-britain-wedding-fund-idUSTRE72F3BK20110316 |title=William and Catherine set up royal wedding charity fund |publisher= [[Reuters]] |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate= 23 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{dead link|date=July 2013}} {{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2011-03/16/content_12183222.htm |title=William and Catherine set up royal wedding charity fund | work = [[China Daily]] |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| author = Staff | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/life-style/weddings/4778882/William-and-Kates-gift-to-Christchurch |title=William and Catherine's gift to Christchurch |publisher= [[Fairfax New Zealand|Fairfax NZ News]] (via [[stuff.co.nz]]) |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate= 23 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author = Garton, Christie | url=http://yourlife.usatoday.com/mind-soul/doing-good/kindness/post/2011/04/in-lieu-of-gifts-prince-william-and-kate-middleton-request-charity-donations-instead/148363/1 |title=No wedding gifts, please: William and Catherine request charity donations instead | work = [[USA Today]] |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate= 23 July 2013}}</ref>

===Sports===
[[File:Prince William and Prince Charles.jpg|thumb|right|William and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|his father, Charles]], after a polo match at [[Ham Polo Club]], [[London]]]]
William plays [[polo]] for charitable causes. He is a fan of [[association football|football]] and supports [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Prince George to support Aston Villa, says William |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24682512 |publisher=BBC News |date=26 October 2013 |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> He became President of [[The Football Association|England's Football Association]] in May 2006 and vice royal patron of the [[Welsh Rugby Union]] (WRU) in February 2007 (supporting the Queen as patron of the WRU).<ref name="POWPatron" /> The same year, the WRU's decision to name a new cup for test matches between Wales and [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] the [[Prince William Cup]] caused controversy, with some believing it would have been more fitting to name the trophy after [[Ray Gravell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/rugbynation/rugby-in-wales/2007/11/24/prince-william-to-watch-namesake-cup-tie-91466-20155814/ |title=Prince William to watch namesake cup tie |publisher=WalesOnline |date=24 November 2007 |accessdate=29 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126041822/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/rugbynation/rugby-in-wales/2007/11/24/prince-william-to-watch-namesake-cup-tie-91466-20155814/ |archivedate=26 January 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/230 |title=UK Parliament – Early Day Motion 230 |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/7110794.stm |title=Prince watches Wales lose his cup |publisher=BBC News |date=24 November 2007 |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>

In 2006, William, along with other Sandhurst officers, took part in running one mile to support the charity [[Sport Relief]], as he had done in 2004 with a team from [[Clarence House]]. In May 2007, William became patron of the English Schools' Swimming Association.<ref name="POWPatron" /> In 2013 he succeeded his grandfather the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] as president of the UK charity [[Fields in Trust]], formerly the [[National Playing Fields Association]].<ref name=NFPA>{{cite web|url=http://www.fieldsintrust.org/Royal_patronage.aspx|website=Fields in Trust|title=Royal Patronage}}</ref>

In December 2010, William and British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] attended a meeting with [[FIFA]] vice-president [[Chung Mong-joon]] in which Chung suggested a vote-trading deal for the right to host the 2018 World Cup in England. The English delegation reported the attempt to FIFA's ethics investigator because they considered vote-swapping to be a violation of anti-collusion rules.<ref>"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/27/prince-william-david-cameron-caught-fifa-corruption-scandal/ Prince William and David Cameron caught up in Fifa corruption scandal]". ''The Daily Telegraph.'' 27 June 2017.</ref><ref>"[https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/video-news/video-david-cameron-and-prince-william-implicated-in-fifa-corruption-probe-35874189.html Video: David Cameron and Prince William implicated in FIFA corruption probe]". ''Belfast Telegraph''. 28 June 2017.</ref>

William and his brother are both enthusiastic motorcyclists, with William owning a [[Ducati 1198|Ducati 1198 S Corse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Biking runs in Royal blood|url=https://www.motorcyclenews.com/news/2016/march/mcn-plus---picture-story-four-princes/|accessdate=21 May 2018|publisher=Motorcycle News|date=21 February 2018}}</ref>

In May 2014 the Duke followed in the footsteps of his father and grandfather to become president of the [[British Sub-Aqua Club]] (BSAC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsac.com/page.asp?section%3D4623%26sectionTitle%3DBSAC+President |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904080208/http://www.bsac.com/page.asp?section=4623&sectionTitle=BSAC%2BPresident |archivedate=4 September 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>

==Personal life==

===Bachelorhood===
As with his father, William's private life became the subject of tabloid speculation, especially around his relationship with [[Catherine Middleton]], who had been one of William's university [[Roommate|flatmates]] and whom William began dating in 2003. Middleton attended William's passing-out parade at Sandhurst, which was the first high-profile event that she attended as his guest. The relationship between them was followed so closely that [[bookmaker]]s took bets on the possibility of marriage, and the retail chain [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]] produced [[Souvenir|memorabilia]] bearing the likenesses of the couple.<ref name="CTV Split">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/prince-william-girlfriend-end-their-relationship-1.237322 |title=Prince William, girlfriend end their relationship |publisher=CTV News |date=14 April 2007 |accessdate=16 October 2008}}</ref> Media attention became so intense that William formally  asked the press to keep their distance from Middleton.<ref name="CTV Split" />

It was reported in April 2007 that the couple had split,<ref name="CTV Split" /> though Middleton, in June, attended a party at [[Lulworth Camp]] as a guest of Prince William and in July the [[Concert for Diana]], which had been organised by Princes William and Harry. In subsequent months, she accompanied William on holiday and joined the Royal Family on private outings and at public events.

===Marriage and fatherhood===
{{main|Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton}}
[[File:Canada Ottawa William Kate 2011 (2).jpg|thumb|right|The Duke and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]] at the official Canada Day celebration in Ottawa, 2011, during their first tour outside the United Kingdom]]
On 16 November 2010, Clarence House announced that Prince William and Middleton were to marry; the couple had become engaged in Kenya in October.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.royal.uk/his-royal-highness-prince-william-wales-and-miss-catherine-middleton-are-engaged-be-married | title=His Royal Highness Prince William of Wales and Miss Catherine Middleton are engaged to be married | publisher=Website of the Royal Family | date=16 November 2010}}</ref> The engagement ring given by William to Catherine was [[Engagement ring of Diana, Princess of Wales|that which had belonged to his mother]].

The wedding took place on 29 April 2011 in [[Westminster Abbey]], London.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13229961 |title=Crowds cheer newly-wed couple |publisher=BBC News |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref> A few hours prior to the ceremony, William's new titles of [[Duke of Cambridge]], [[Earl of Strathearn]], and [[Baron Carrickfergus]] were announced.<ref name=titles>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2011/Announcementoftitles29April2011.aspx |title=Announcement of titles |date=29 April 2011 |publisher=[[Buckingham Palace]] |accessdate=29 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430090334/http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2011/Announcementoftitles29April2011.aspx |archivedate=30 April 2011 }}</ref><ref name=BBC-titles>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13236409 |title=Kate and William become Duke and Duchess of Cambridge |publisher=BBC News |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Beckford |first=Martin |date=29 April 2011 |title=Prince William and Kate Middleton's new titles revealed |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8482573/Prince-William-and-Kate-Middletons-new-titles-revealed.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=3 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Beckford |first=Martin |date=29 April 2011 |title=Royal wedding: Prince William and Kate Middleton become Duke and Duchess of Cambridge |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8482962/Royal-wedding-Prince-William-and-Kate-Middleton-become-Duke-and-Duchess-of-Cambridge.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>

His wife's first pregnancy was announced on 3 December 2012.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-20586343 |title=Duchess of Cambridge pregnant |publisher=BBC News |date=3 December 2012 |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> She was admitted on 22 July 2013 to the Lindo Wing, [[St Mary's Hospital, London]], where Prince William himself had been delivered. Later that day, she gave birth to a son – [[Prince George of Cambridge|Prince George]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Saul |first=Heather |date=24 July 2013 |title=Royal baby: The prince meets his people in world media frenzy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/royal-baby-the-prince-meets-his-people-in-world-media-frenzy-8727931.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23413653 |title=Royal baby: Kate gives birth to boy |publisher=BBC News |date=22 July 2013 |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> On 8 September 2014, it was announced that the Duchess of Cambridge was pregnant with her second child.<ref name="bbc2ndbaby">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-29108010 |title=Royal baby: Prince William and Kate expecting second child |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> She was admitted on 2 May 2015 to the same hospital where she had first given birth and gave birth to [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge|Princess Charlotte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32562117|title=Royal baby: Duchess of Cambridge gives birth to daughter|publisher=BBC News|date=2 May 2015|accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref> The Duchess's third pregnancy was announced on 4 September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41148027|title=Royal baby: Duchess of Cambridge expecting third child|publisher=BBC|date=4 September 2017}}</ref> [[Prince Louis of Cambridge|Prince Louis]] was born on 23 April 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43864933| title=Royal baby: Duchess of Cambridge gives birth to boy| date=April 23, 2018| website=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>

In March 2017, a video of William dancing with an unidentified woman at the Farinet night club in [[Verbier]], Switzerland, surfaced in the media.<ref name="Vanity-Club">{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/03/kate-middleton-prince-william-ski-trip|title=Kate Middleton Is "Less than Pleased" with Prince William’s Ski-Trip Behavior|publisher=Vanity Fair|first=Katie|last=Nicholl|date=16 March 2017|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> At the time, he was on a skiing holiday with his friends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/prince-william-dancing-swiss-nightclub-2017-3|title=Prince William was caught 'dad dancing' in a Swiss nightclub|publisher=Business Insider|first=Francesca|last=Gillett|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> The press criticised William's behaviour since he had also skipped the [[Commonwealth Day]] service at Westminster Abbey which was attended by other senior members of the royal family.<ref name="Vanity-Club"/>

==Titles, styles, honours and arms==

===Titles and styles===
* 1982<!--Born 21 June, but name only announced on 28 June-->–2011: His Royal Highness Prince William of Wales
* 2011–present: His Royal Highness The [[Duke of Cambridge]] 
** In Scotland: His Royal Highness The [[Earl of Strathearn]]<ref name="scot">{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/new-appointments-order-thistle-0 |title=New appointments to the Order of the Thistle, 29 May 2012 |publisher=Official website of the British royal family}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dukeandduchessofcambridge.org/news-and-diary/the-duke-and-duchess-of-cambridge-visit-glasgow Duke and Duchess of Cambridge – visit the Emirates Arena] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806105612/http://www.dukeandduchessofcambridge.org/news-and-diary/the-duke-and-duchess-of-cambridge-visit-glasgow |date=6 August 2013 }} "The Duke and Duchess, known as the Earl and Countess of Strathearn when in Scotland..." (Accessed 24 July 2013)</ref><ref>[http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/the-prince-of-wales/the-princes-charities/dumfries-house Prince of Wales – Dumfries House] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626002826/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/the-prince-of-wales/the-princes-charities/dumfries-house |date=26 June 2013 }} (Section: April 5th Official Opening of the Tamar Manoukian Outdoor Centre) "...Their Royal Highnesses The Prince Charles, Duke of Rothesay and the Earl and Countess of Strathearn..." (Accessed 24 July 2013)</ref>
** In Northern Ireland: [[Baron Carrickfergus]]<ref>[http://uk.businessinsider.com/prince-william-kate-middleton-and-prince-charles-have-different-names-when-they-go-to-scotland-and-ireland-heres-what-they-are-2018-1? Prince William, Kate Middleton, and Prince Charles have different names when they go to Scotland and Ireland — here's what they are] - website of [[Business Insider|UK Business Insider]]</ref><ref>[http://www.countryliving.co.uk/wildlife/countryside/news/a3285/kate-middleton-different-name-scotland-northern-ireland/ The Duchess of Cambridge has a different name in Scotland and Northern Ireland] - website of Country Living UK</ref>

The hereditary titles of [[Duke of Cambridge]], [[Earl of Strathearn]] and [[Baron Carrickfergus]] were announced on 29 April 2011 and formally patented 26 May.<ref name="titles" />{{refn|name=name|group=fn|The [[Letters Patent]] formalising these titles were signed and passed under the [[Great Seal of the Realm|Great Seal]] on 26 May 2011.<ref name=LG5978>{{London Gazette |issue=59798 |page=10297 |date=1 June 2011 |nolink=yes}}</ref>}} William is a Royal [[Knight Companion of the Most Noble Order of the Garter]] (KG),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/PrinceWilliam/Stylesandtitles.aspx |title=The Duke of Cambridge: Styles and Titles |publisher=Royal |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414152844/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/PrinceWilliam/Stylesandtitles.aspx |archivedate=14 April 2012 }}</ref> a [[Knight of the Most Ancient and Most Noble Order of the Thistle]] (KT),<ref name="scot" /> a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] (PC), and a [[Personal Aide-de-Camp]] (ADC(P)) to the Queen.<ref name="AidedeCamp">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/prince-william/9935850/Duke-of-Cambridge-becomes-Aide-de-Camp-to-the-Queen.html | title=Duke of Cambridge becomes Aide-de-Camp to the Queen | work=The Telegraph | date=17 March 2013 | accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>

As a [[British prince]], William does not use a surname for everyday purposes. For formal and ceremonial purposes, the children of the Prince of Wales use the title of "prince" or "princess" before their [[Christian name]] and their father's territorial designation after it. Thus, Prince William was styled as "Prince William of Wales". Such territorial designations are discarded by women when they marry and by men if they are given a [[peerage]] of their own,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5657.asp |title=Titles and succession: Royal Family name|publisher=Royal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080804094423/http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5657.asp |archivedate=4 August 2008|accessdate=15 October 2008}}</ref> such as when Prince William was given his dukedom.

For the male-line grandchildren of Elizabeth II, however, there is currently some uncertainty over the correct form of family surname to use, or even whether there is a surname. The Queen has stipulated that all her male-line descendants "who do not bear the titular dignity of prince" shall use Mountbatten-Windsor as their family surname (although Letters Patent exist stipulating the name Windsor, but with the same caveat). Princes William and Harry both used Wales as their surname for military purposes; this continues to be the case for William since his creation as Duke of Cambridge.<ref name="Duke of Cambridge, Flt Lt Wales">{{cite web|url=http://www.dukeandduchessofcambridge.org/news-and-diary/working-day-the-life-of-flight-lieutenant-wales |title=A working day in the life of Flight Lieutenant Wales |publisher=[[Clarence House]] |date=20 November 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2013 |quote=The Duke of Cambridge – who is known in his Royal Air Force working life as Flight Lieutenant Wales |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130091753/http://www.dukeandduchessofcambridge.org/news-and-diary/working-day-the-life-of-flight-lieutenant-wales |archivedate=30 January 2013 |df= }}</ref>

